  {name: "Safebrew Abbey Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "DCL/Fermentis", product_id: "BE-256", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 200.0, min_attenuation: 81.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 59.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "Abbey Ales\n    Notes: Active dry yeast recommended to brew a diversity of beers amongst which abbey style beers known for their high alcohol content. It ferments very fast and reveals subtle and well-balanced aromas. To maintain the aromatic profile at the end of the fermentation crop the yeast as soon as possible after fermentation."},
  {name: "Saflager Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "DCL/Fermentis", product_id: "W-34/70", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Dry", cell_count: 200.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 77.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 48.0, max_temperature: 59.0, description: "European lagers\n    Notes: A famous yeast strain from Weihenstephan Germany used worldwide in brewing.  Their most popular strain for lagers."},
  {name: "Saison", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Brewtek", product_id: "CL-0380", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 74.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "French or Belgian Ales and Grand Cru styles.\n    Notes: Pleasant yeast blend.  Leaves a smooth full character to the malt with mild, but pleasant esters and some apple pie spices."},
  {name: "Saison Blend", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY027", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Saison, Farmhouse Ale, Belgian Ale, Biere de Garde\n    Notes: A blend of Saison yeast. This Blend is a super robust attenuator that produces a complex flavor profile of fruit and spice."},
  {name: "Saison Blend", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Yeast Bay", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 78.0, max_attenuation: 84.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 66.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "Saison\n    Notes: A blend of two unique yeast strains isolated from beers that embody the saison style, this blend is a balance of the many characteristic saison flavors and aromas. One yeast strain is a good attenuator that produces a spicy and mildly tart and tangy beer with a full mouthfeel. The other yeast strain is also a good attenuator that produces a delightful ester profile of grapefruit and orange zest and imparts a long, dry and earthy finish to the beer. Together, they produce a dry but balanced beer with a unique flavor and aroma profile."},
  {name: "Saison Blend II", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Yeast Bay", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 86.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Saison, Farmhouse ale\n    Notes: This saison blend is the Saccharomyces portion of our Farmhouse Sour Ale, available to you as a result of popular demand from the commercial brewing crowd. This combination of Saccharomyces strains embodies the balanced fusion of the two foremost saison flavor/aroma characters, fruitiness and earthiness.\n\n    Each Saccharomyces strain in this blend produces flavor compounds that serve as the yin to the other&#39;s yang, and the result is an exceptionally complex yet balanced flavor and aroma profile. One strain will serve to create an ester profile of grapefruit and orange zest, while the other will produce a mild earthiness and spiciness."},
  {name: "Saison Brasserie", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "East Coast Yeast", product_id: "ECY08", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 78.0, max_attenuation: 82.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 75.0, max_temperature: 85.0, description: "Saison, Farmhouse Ale, Belgian Ale, Biere de Garde\n    Notes: A combination of several saison yeast strains for both fruity and spicy characteristics accompanied with dryness (attenuation ~ 80%). Suggested fermentation temperature: 75-85F.\n  "},
  {name: "Saison Single", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "East Coast Yeast", product_id: "ECY14", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 76.0, max_attenuation: 78.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 72.0, max_temperature: 78.0, description: "Saison, Farmhouse Ale, Belgian Ale, Biere de Garde\n    Notes: This strain leaves a smooth, full farmhouse character with mild esters reminiscent of apple pie spice. Attenuation 76-78%; fermentation temperature: 75-82F.  "},
  {name: "Saison Sour", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GB124", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 79.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Saison, Lambic, Berliner Weiss, Sour Brown and Gueze\n    Notes: Lactic Acid Bacteria are inhibited by hops, high gravity and low temperatures. You can adjust sourness by increasing or decreasing these variables. More than 7 IBU, gravity above 1050 or temps below 65 F will increase the time to sour or lead to reduced overall souring. Warmer fermentation temps will typically increase the esters and spicy phenolics of the saison ale yeast in this blend."},
  {name: "Saison Yeast One", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY018", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 81.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Saison, Farmhouse Ale, Belgian Ale, Biere de Garde\n    Notes: Traditional Saison yeast from a French craft brewery.  Produces fragrant beer with pepper and fruit notes.  Warmer fermentations create more intense flavors.   Perfect for accentuating citrus and fruit flavors.  High attenuation rates make a dryer beer than Saison #2"},
  {name: "Saison Yeast Two", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY027", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 79.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Saison, Farmhouse Ale, Belgian Ale, Biere de Garde\n    Notes: From a traditional farmhouse Saison. Creates the fruity/spicy aroma traditional to the style.  Warmer fermentation temps result in more intense flavor.  Produces a tartness not found in most of our yeast and a slightly sweeter beer than GY018 (Saison #1)."},
  {name: "Sake #9 Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP709", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 72.0, max_attenuation: 78.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "Sake and rice based wines\n    Notes: For use in rice-based fermentations. Traditional strain used in Ginjo-shu production because of the yeast&rsquo;s development of high fragrance components. Also a fairly strong fermenter, but producing a foamless fermentation."},
  {name: "Sake Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP705", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 86.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 70.0, max_temperature: 76.0, description: "Sake wine yeast\n    Notes: For use in rice based fermentations. For sake, use this yeast in conjunction with Koji (to produce fermentable sugar). WLP705 produces full body sake character, and subtle fragrance.  Alcohol tolerance to 16%."},
  {name: "San Diego Super Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP090", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 76.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 65.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "A wide variety of styles requiring clean, fast fermentation and finish\n    Notes: A super clean, super-fast fermenting strain. A low ester-producing strain that results in a balanced, neutral flavor and aroma profile. Alcohol-tolerant and very versatile for a wide variety of styles. Similar to California Ale Yeast WLP001 but it generally ferments faster."},
  {name: "San Francisco Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP810", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 65.0, max_attenuation: 70.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 58.0, max_temperature: 65.0, description: "California and Premium Lagers, all American Lagers\n    Notes: Produces &quot;California Common&quot; style beer."},
  {name: "Scotch Ale One", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY044", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 82.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Scotch Ale, Pale Ale, Wee Heavy, Brown Ale, Porter, Stout\n    Notes: This is one sweet yeast.  Neutral flavors emphasize the malt.  Leaves a slight residual sweetness and body in high gravity beers perfect for malt forward styles like scotch ales, wee heavy, stouts and porters."},
  {name: "Scotch Whisky Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP045", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 75.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 72.0, max_temperature: 77.0, description: "Scotch Whiskey Yeast\n    Notes: A strain that was widely used for Scotch Whisky production from the early 1950s, producing a complex array of ester compounds and fusel oils, as well as some spicy, clove character. Suitable for Scotch Whisky or American-style Whiskey. Used in high-gravity beers."},
  {name: "Scottish Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Brewtek", product_id: "CL-0200", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "Scottish ales\n    Notes: Use for classic Scottish heavys, 90&#39;s- or strong ales. This yeast produces a soft, fruity malt profile with a subtle woody, oakey ester profile. A mild, mineral like dryness in the finish makes this a very complex strain."},
  {name: "Scottish Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-015", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 70.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 65.0, max_temperature: 70.0, description: "Scottish Ale, Scottish Strong Ales, Sweet Stout, Imperial Stout, Barley Wine\n    Notes: Produces complex, flavorful Scottish style ales. Often used as a &ldquo;house&rdquo; strain. Hop character is not muted with this strain."},
  {name: "Scottish Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1728", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 69.0, max_attenuation: 73.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 55.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Scottish Ale, Scottish Strong Ales, Sweet Stout, Imperial Stout, Barley Wine\n    Notes: High alcohol tolerance."},
  {name: "Scottish Bitter", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Brewtek", product_id: "CL-0210", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "Scottish Ales\n    Notes: CL-210 has a soft, yeasty, fruity nose which yields to a well attenuated malt flavor and big ester complex of ripe fruit, apricots and rose petals. Dry and complex, yet smooth and fruity with mild sulphur. "},
  {name: "Scottish Heavy", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "East Coast Yeast", product_id: "ECY07", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "Heavy Ales, 90/ Shilling, Barley wine\n    Notes: Leaves a fruity profile with woody, oak esters reminiscent of malt whiskey. Well suited for 90/ shilling or heavier ales including old ales and barleywines due to the level of attenuation (77-80%). Suggested fermentation temperature: 60-68F."},
  {name: "Scourmont Abbey", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY014", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 79.0, max_attenuation: 81.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Belgian Ale, Dubbel, Belgian Strong, Tripel, Beire de Garde, Saison\n    Notes: Classic Belgian yeast from one of the best known Trappist breweries.  A fragrant yeast that produces delicious fruity aroma.  Good choice for high gravity beers.  Generally, the warmer this yeast is fermented the higher the level of fruit aromas produced."},
  {name: "Sour Cherry Funk", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GB150", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 50.0, max_attenuation: 52.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Sours\n    Notes: This blend creates an amazing complex, sour beer with fruity cherry esters.  Fermenting in the presence of 7-10 IBUs will cause the fermentation to complete much more quickly but will slow the souring &mdash;  expect to wait 3-4 months for significant souring.  Fermenting with zero or less than 5 IBUs will allow souring to happen much faster (within two weeks) but will cause the fermentation to take up to 4 weeks to complete."},
  {name: "Sour Plum Belgian", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GB123", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 76.0, max_attenuation: 78.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Trapist Ales, Sours\n    Notes: Lactic Acid Bacteria are inhibited by hops, high gravity and low temperatures. You can adjust sourness by increasing or decreasing these variables. More than 7 IBU, gravity above 1050 or temps below 65 F will increase the time to sour or lead to reduced overall souring. Warmer fermentation temps will typically increase the esters and spicy phenolics of the saison ale yeast in this blend."},
  {name: "Southern German Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP838", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 68.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 50.0, max_temperature: 55.0, description: "German Pilsner, Helles, Oktoberfest, Marzen, Bocks\n    Notes: Malty finish and balanced aroma.  Strong fermenter, slight sulfur and low diacetyl."},
  {name: "Southwold Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP025", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 68.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 66.0, max_temperature: 69.0, description: "British bitters and pale ales.\n    Notes: From Suffolk county.  Products complex fruity and citrus flavors.  Slight sulfer production, but this will fade with ageing."},
  {name: "Special Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Glenbrew", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 200.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 77.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "All-malt beers.\n    Notes: Highly attentive, clean finish dry yeast."},
  {name: "Steinberg-Geisenheim Wine", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP727", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 86.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 50.0, max_temperature: 90.0, description: "Riesling wines.\n    Notes: German origin wine yeast.  High fruit/ester production.  Moderate fermentation characteristics and cold tolerant."},
  {name: "Summation Red", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "4267", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 85.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 59.0, max_temperature: 89.6, description: "Cabernet, Malbec, Port, Sauvignon Blanc, Merlot\n    Notes: Produces distinctive intense berry, graham cracker nose. Jammy, rich, very smooth complex profile, slightly vinous. Well suited to higher sugar content musts. "},
  {name: "Super High Gravity Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP099", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 84.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 69.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "Very high gravity beers and barley wine up to 25% alcohol.\n    Notes: Ferments up to 25% alcohol content.  Flavor may vary greatly depending on beer alcohol.  English like esters at low gravity, but will become more wine-like as alcohol exceeds 16% ABV.  Refer to White Labs web page for tips on fermenting high gravity ales."},
  {name: "Suremain Burgundy Wine Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP770", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 86.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 90.0, description: "Burgundy\n    Notes: Emphasizes fruit aromas in barrel fermentations. High nutrient requirement to avoid volatile acidity production.\n    Alcohol Tolerance: 16%"},
  {name: "Sweet Flemish Brettt", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GB144", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 82.0, max_attenuation: 84.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Belgian Lambic, Gueze Lambic, and Sour Browns\n    Notes: Brew with GB144 on it&rsquo;s own to make an all brett beer, in a primary fermentation with an ale yeast for a complex blended profile or in a secondary to add character during aging."},
  {name: "Sweet Mead", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "4184", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 85.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 64.4, max_temperature: 75.2, description: "Common cider, sweet mead, Braggot\n    Notes: Leaves 2-3% residual sugar in most meads. Rich, fruity profile complements fruit mead fermentations. Use of Vintner&#39;s Choice yeast nutrient is recommended. "},
  {name: "Sweet Mead/Wine", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP720", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 70.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 70.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Sweet Mead, Wine and Cider\n    Notes: Lower attenuation than White Labs Champagne Yeast.  Leaves some residual sweetness as well as fruity flavor.  Alcohol concentration up to 15%."},
  {name: "Sweet White", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "4783", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 80.0, max_attenuation: 85.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 55.4, max_temperature: 75.2, description: "Braggot, Cider, Dry Mead, Icewine, Fruit cider, Sweet mead, Vermouth\n    Notes: Produces distinct Riesling character. Rich flavor, creamy, fruity profile with nice dry finish and a hint of Riesling sweetness in the aftertaste. "},
  {name: "Swiss Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Brewtek", product_id: "CL-0670", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 74.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 48.0, max_temperature: 54.0, description: "European pilsners and lagers\n    Notes: A unique strain that has both a clean, crisp lager flavor and a soft, smooth maltiness. Perfect for European Pilsners. Like our CL-660 strain, this is an excellent all purpose Lager yeast for those wanting a fuller, rounder palate. "},
  {name: "Swiss Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-112", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 70.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 50.0, max_temperature: 55.0, description: "Swiss style lager, and high gravity lagers (over 11% ABV)\n    Notes: This yeast can be used to produce lager beer over 11% ABV. Sulfur and diacetyl production is minimal."},
  {name: "Tart Cherry Brett", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GB002", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 78.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Belgian Lambic, Gueze Lambic, and Sour Browns\n    Notes: Produces some Brett Barnyard funk plus stone fruit and cherry-like esters.  This Strain also produces a moderate amount of acid that adds a tart complexity to the brew.\n\n    This yeast is highly attenuative but tends to ferment about &frac12; as fast as a typical ale strain.  Although it attenuates faster than GB001, it is typically best used in combination with faster fermenting yeast in the primary or added to the secondary to add complexity while aging."},
  {name: "Tennessee Whisky Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP050", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 75.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 75.0, max_temperature: 79.0, description: "American Whisky\n    Notes: Suitable for American-style whiskey and bourbon. This yeast is famous for creating rich, smooth flavors. Clean and dry fermenting yeast. Will tolerate high alcohol concentrations (15%), and ester production is low. Also popular in high-gravity beers."},
  {name: "Thames Valley Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1275", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 76.0, max_attenuation: 78.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "British Bitters, ESB, India Pale Ale, English Strong Ale\n    Notes: Clean, complex flavor.  Low in fruit, low in esters, rich in flavor.  Hops come through well."},
  {name: "Top", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Brewferm", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 200.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 77.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 64.4, max_temperature: 77.0, description: "American IPA, Dark ales, Witbier\n    Notes: Top fermenting yeast that most suitable for amber coloured and dark beers. Fast\n    fermentation with low residual sugar. Formation of fruity esters."},
  {name: "Trappist Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP500", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 75.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 65.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "Trappist Ale, Dubbel, Trippel, Belgian Ales\n    Notes: Distinctive fruitiness and plum characteristics.  Excellent for high gravity beers."},
  {name: "Trappist High Gravity", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "3787", yeast_type: "Wheat", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 74.0, max_attenuation: 78.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 78.0, description: "Belgian Wit, Trappist Ale, High gravity ales\n    Notes: Robust top cropping yeast.  Phenolic character and alcohol tolerance up to 12%.  Rich ester profile and malty flavor."},
  {name: "Trappist Tripel", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY015", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 74.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 66.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "Belgian Ale, Dubbel, Belgian Strong, Tripel, Biere de Garde, Saison\n    Notes: Trappist Ale yeast from the mother of all Tripels.  A balance of fruit and spice with a  good malty finish provides a perfect complement for Belgian Ales, Dubbels and Tripels.   Attenuation is on the slow side leaving more residual sweetness than our other Belgians. Less esters and phenolics than GY003 and GY014."},
  {name: "Tropical IPA", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-200", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 85.0, max_attenuation: 90.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 75.0, max_temperature: 85.0, description: "Sour beers, Belgian Sour Variations\n    Notes: A unique strain formerly classified as Brettanomyces but since found to be Saccharomyces.  Produces a beer with tropical fruit characteristics of mango and pineapple. Can also be used to produce effervescence when bottle-conditioning."},
  {name: "Urquell Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "2001", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 72.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 48.0, max_temperature: 58.0, description: "Bohemian Pilsner\n    Notes: Pilsner Urquell yeast with mild fruit/floral aroma.  Very dry and clean on palate with full mouth feel.  Subtle malt character.  Clean and neutral finish."},
  {name: "Vermont Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Yeast Bay", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 70.0, description: "IPA\n    Notes: Isolated from a uniquely crafted double IPA out of the Northeastern United States, this yeast produces a balanced fruity ester profile of peaches and light citrus that complements any aggressively hopped beer. Expect this strain to take off fast and ferment wort quickly, though elevating the temperature following the bulk of fermentation may be required to raise the attenuation.\n\n    In order to achieve high attenuation, we recommend fermenting at 64-68 &ordm;F for 5-7 days, and then raising the temperature to 70 &ordm;F until a stable gravity is reached. We also recommend mashing at 148-149 &ordm;F and adding a small percentage of the fermentables (~ 5-10%) as sugar."},
  {name: "Vermont IPA", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY054", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 78.0, max_attenuation: 82.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "IPA, American Wheat, Pale Ale, Bitter, West Coast Amber, ESB\n    Notes: From one of the best examples of an east coast IPA.  This yeast attenuates slightly less than NorCal Ale #1 and leaves a beer with more body and a slight fruity ester that is amazing with aromatic hops.  Good choice for high gravity beers and hoppy styles.  Broad temperature range and moderate flocculation make this yeast a versatile house strain."},
  {name: "Voss Kveik", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-062", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 75.0, max_attenuation: 82.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 98.0, description: "Ales\n    Notes: A traditional Norwegian &ldquo;kveik&rdquo; strain from the farmhouse brewery of Sigmund Gjernes in Voss, Norway, this strain (like OYL-057 HotHead) is capable of fermenting across a broad temperature range with little change in flavor profile.  Voss Kveik is non-phenolic and produces a beer with moderate citrus notes.  It would pair very well with citrusy and fruity hops.  This strain is not fast at the low end of the range so don&rsquo;t be afraid to pitch in the middle to upper part of the temperature range."},
  {name: "Wallonian Farmhouse", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Yeast Bay", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 81.0, max_attenuation: 88.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 72.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Farmhouse ale, Belgian ale\n    Notes: Isolated from a unique farmhouse-style ale that hails from the Walloon region of Belgium, this yeast is one of the funkiest &quot;clean&quot; yeast we have in our stable. It imparts a slight earthy funk and tart character to the beer, and is a very mild producer of some slightly spicy and mildly smokey flavor compounds.\n\n    This yeast exhibits absurdly high attenuation, resulting in a practically bone-dry beer. If desired, we recommend controlling the dryness by adjusting the mash temperature or adding malts or adjuncts to the mash tun that will lend some body and residual sweetness to the beer.\n\n    When fermented cool this yeast will provide a cleaner profile, and the character development will increase proportionally with increasing fermentation temperature."},
  {name: "Weihenstephan Weizen", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "3068", yeast_type: "Wheat", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 77.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Bavarian Weizen\n    Notes: Unique Bavarian wheat yeast that produces the spicy weizen clove and banana flavor.  Best when fermented at around 68 deg F."},
  {name: "West Coast Ale I", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-004", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 73.0, description: "American Style Ales, Ambers, Pale Ales, Brown Ale, Strong Ale\n    Notes: Clean, crisp flavor characteristics with low fruitiness and mild ester production. A very versatile yeast for styles that desire dominant malt and hop character. A very popular &ldquo;house&rdquo; strain. May yield citrus notes with cooler 60-66&deg;F fermentations."},
  {name: "West Coast II", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-009", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 72.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "American style Pales, Ambers, Browns, IPAs, American Strong Ale\n    Notes: A versatile strain and a good choice for a &ldquo;House&rdquo; strain. Provides a soft, clean profile with hints of nut, and a slightly tart finish. Ferment at warmer temperatures to accentuate hop character with an increased fruitiness. Or, ferment cool for a clean, light citrus character. It attenuates well and is reliably flocculent, producing bright beer without filtration."},
  {name: "West Coast III", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-043", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 76.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 65.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "A wide variety of styles requiring clean, fast fermentation and finish.\n    Notes: A clean, fast fermenting strain similar to West Coast Ale I. A low ester-producing strain that results in a balanced, neutral flavor and aroma profile. Alcohol-tolerant and very versatile for a wide variety of styles."},
  {name: "West Coast IV", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-050", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "West-coast style American craft beers, especially pale, IPA, red, and specialties\n    Notes: Excellent attenuation, temperature tolerance, and good flocculation make this an easy strain to work with. Flavor is balanced neutral with mild ester formation at warmer temps, allowing hops, character malts, and flavorings to show through."},
  {name: "West Coast Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-105", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 67.0, max_attenuation: 71.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 58.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "California and Premium Lagers, all American Lagers\n    Notes: Produces California Common-style beers. Retains lager characteristics at temperatures up to 65&deg;F and produces malty, brilliantly clear beers. This strain is not recommended for cold temperature fermentation."},
  {name: "West Yorkshire Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1469", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 67.0, max_attenuation: 71.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "English IPA, Bitters, Stouts, Browns\n    Notes: This strain produces ales with a full chewy malt flavor and character, but finishes dry, producing famously balanced beers. Expect moderate nutty and stone-fruit esters. Best used for the production of cask-conditioned bitters, ESB and mild ales. Reliably flocculent, producing bright beer without filtration."},
  {name: "Where Da Funk?", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-210", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 78.0, max_attenuation: 88.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Lambic\n    Notes: A blend of a mild Brettanomyces isolate from a Colorado brewery known for its Brett beers and two strains formerly classified as Brettanomyces but since found to be Saccharomyces. This blend produces huge tropical fruit aromas during fermentation that fade somewhat during conditioning. Has a wide temperature range and ferments very dry, leaving little body. Consider adding flaked oats if additional body is desired. This blend will not produce significant &ldquo;funk&rdquo; or acid, even with extended aging. The blend pairs well with fruity aroma hops to make a unique pale ale."},
  {name: "Whitbread Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1099", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 68.0, max_attenuation: 72.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Whitbread Ale, British Ales, Pales, Bitters\n    Notes: Slightly more fruity and malty than Wyeast&#39;s British Ale.  Clear and highly flocculant."},
  {name: "Whitbread Ale Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP017", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 67.0, max_attenuation: 73.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 66.0, max_temperature: 70.0, description: "English style ales, milds, bitters, porters, and English ales as well as some North Amreican ales\n    Notes: Traditional mixed yeast culture. British style character, slightly fruity, with a hint of sulfur production. This yeast can be used for many different beer styles. The most traditional choices would be English style ales including milds, bitters, porters, and English style stouts. North American style ales will also benefit from fermentation with WLP017. The beer will clear easily."},
  {name: "Windsor Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Lallemand", product_id: "-", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 200.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 77.0, flocculation: 3, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "Ales\n    Notes: Clean, well balanced finish.  Yeast produces an estery ale with a slighly fresh yeast flavor.  Not as quick as the Nottingham.  Some bannana aroma."},
  {name: "Wit", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-030", yeast_type: "Wheat", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 72.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 75.0, description: "Belgian Wit\n    Notes: Produces a complex flavor profile dominated by spicy phenolics with low to moderate ester production. It is a great strain choice when you want a delicate clove profile not to be overshadowed by esters. It will ferment fairly dry with a slightly tart finish that compliments the use of oats, malted and unmalted wheat. This strain is a true top cropping yeast requiring full fermenter headspace of 33%."},
  {name: "Wyeast Ale Blend", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1087", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 71.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "American and British Ale Styles.\n    Notes: Blend of ale strains designed to provide quick starts, good flavor, balance and flocculation.  Balanced finish suitable for most American and British ale styles."},
  {name: "Wyeast Lager Blend", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "2178", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 71.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 48.0, max_temperature: 58.0, description: "Classic Pilsners, Lagers, Bocks.\n    Notes: Blend of lager strains to produce a complex but clean lager flavor profile.  Suitable for many common lager styles."},
  {name: "Yorkshire Square Ale Yeast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP037", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 68.0, max_attenuation: 72.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 65.0, max_temperature: 69.0, description: "English pale ales, English brown ales and Mild ales\n    Notes: This yeast produces a malty but well balanced profile.  Expect toasty flavors with malt driven esters.  Highly flocculent and a good choice for many English ales."},
  {name: "Zurich Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "White Labs", product_id: "WLP885", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 70.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 50.0, max_temperature: 55.0, description: "Swiss style lager, and high gravity lagers (over 11% ABV)\n    Notes: Swiss style lager yeast.  Sulfer and diacytl production is minimal.  May be used for high gravity lagers with proper care."},
  {name: "Bit O' Funk", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Omega", product_id: "OYL-211", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 150.0, min_attenuation: 85.0, max_attenuation: 90.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 68.0, max_temperature: 80.0, description: "Sours, Lambic\n    Notes: This blend contains the two Saccharomyces strains from blend #1 for primary fermentation and is spiked with Brettanomyces bruxellensis for development of moderate &ldquo;funk&rdquo; during a secondary fermentation. The &ldquo;bit &lsquo;o funkiness&rdquo; will take extended time (3+ months) to develop."},
  {name: "English Special Bitter", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1768", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 68.0, max_attenuation: 72.0, flocculation: 3, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "Extra Special, Bitters\n    Notes: Similar to 1968, slightly less flocculent. Produces light fruit ethanol aroma. Mild malt with a neutral soft finish. Very clean. "},
  {name: "West Coast IPA", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1217", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 73.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "American IPA, Imperial IPA, American Pale Ale, American brown ale, Red Ales, Scottish Ales\n    Notes: Thorough attenuation, temp tolerance, and good flocculation make this an easy strain to work with. Flavor is balanced neutral with mild ester formation at warmer temps, allowing hops, character malts, and flavorings to show through."},
  {name: "Bavarian Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M76", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 75.0, max_attenuation: 80.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 45.0, max_temperature: 57.0, description: "Suitable for many European style beers\n    including Lagers, Pilsners, Helles, Munich\n    Dunkel, Rauchbier and more.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    A superlative lager strain that is robust with a light sulphur aroma, expresses hop\n    character well and promotes malt complexity.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Lightly acidic this yeast creates an extremely drinkable lager with less sulphur\n    character than the usual strains.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    This yeast does well at higher gravities having a good attenuation range; high alcohol\n    beers do not tend to be too sweet."},
  {name: "Bavarian Wheat ", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M20", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 70.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 86.0, description: "Suitable for Hefeweizen, Kristal\n    Weizen, Dunkel Weizen and more.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    It has abundant classic banana esters, balanced with clove like phenolic aromas; these\n    aromas tend to overwhelm any malt or hop character in the beer.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    While this strain has only a moderate tendency to attenuate, the final beer will not be\n    sweet. Instead, it will have a creamy, silky mouth feel with a full and rich medium body.\n    This strain strips away most caramel and complex malt flavors, while deep roast and\n    chocolate flavors will come through. The slight acidity produced, greatly enhances wheat\n    malt characteristics. It has a very low flocculation rate that makes it ideal for beers that\n    are traditionally served cloudy.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    In higher alcohol beers, the phenolic character presented by this strain becomes a bit\n    smokey and esters burst forth. Low attenuation rate may result in a sweet beer."},
  {name: "Belgian Tripel", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M31", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 82.0, max_attenuation: 88.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 82.0, description: "Suitable for Belgian Tripel Style and\n    Trappist style beers.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Belgian Tripel has a fantastic heavily fruity aroma, married perfectly with light spice\n    and esters it is massively complex, spicy, estery and phenolic.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Belgian beers fermented with this strain will finish phenolic and dry, they will also\n    exhibit fruity and very complex ester characters. These characters exhibit a beautiful\n    marriage of spice and fruit estery alcohol goodness.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    High alcohol beers are this strain&rsquo;s bread and butter, with a high alcohol tolerance,\n    strong beers just create excellent flavor and aroma characteristics."},
  {name: "Bohemian Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M84", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 72.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 50.0, max_temperature: 59.0, description: "Suitable for German/Bohemian Pilsners,\n    Baltic Porter, and American style Lagers.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Classic Bohemian pilsner strain aroma and flavor characteristics can be expected.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Hop and malt character will be enhanced and supported by moderate to full body. In wort\n    with simple malt bills, delicate malt flavors will survive. Beer fermented with this strain is\n    generally rich and chewy without being heavy at all. Light and delicately balanced beers\n    call for this strain. Lagering periods as short as 4 weeks may produce acceptable beer but\n    allowing it to lager for 6-8 weeks, it will result in beer that is richer and smoother with a\n    more refined aroma and flavor.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    This strain will perform reasonably well in higher alcohol beer production up to 8%\n    alcohol. Beer of over 7% alcohol will be slightly sweet, and the alcohol may be slightly hot."},
  {name: "French Saison Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M29", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 85.0, max_attenuation: 90.0, flocculation: 1, min_temperature: 79.0, max_temperature: 90.0, description: "Suitable for producing Saisons and\n    farmhouse style beers up to 14% ABV.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    This French Saison ale yeast strain brings all the sophistication and complexity of\n    classic Saison ale production to the home brew and small brewery setting. Spicy and\n    peppery characteristics are prominent with an undertone of the ubiquitous fruity\n    character.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    This is a highly characterful yeast strain that will dominate all but the highest hopping\n    rates and complex malt bills. Beers fermented with this yeast will tend to be dry in\n    the finish often with a slight drying acidity and peppery notes, aiding drinkability at\n    higher alcohol levels. Higher alcohol beers may have an increased ester production and\n    warming alcohol notes.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    This yeast strain will perform exceptionally well up to 14% ABV making it suitable for a\n    large range of Saisons."},
  {name: "Mead", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M05", yeast_type: "Wine", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 95.0, max_attenuation: 100.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 59.0, max_temperature: 86.0, description: "Suitable for all styles of mead.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    This strain promotes fresh, floral aromas through high ester production, especially at\n    cooler temperatures.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Meads fermented with this strain will finish dry and be relatively full-bodied with good\n    complexity and a fresh, floral character.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    This strain has high alcohol tolerance up to 18% ABV.\n    For higher alcohol meads, ferment cooler; below 77&deg;F (25&deg;C)."},
  {name: "US West Coast", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M44", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 85.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "Suitable for American Style Pale Ales, American\n    Double IPAs, American Style Imperial Stouts\n    and more.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    A very neutral strain even when fermented in higher gravity worts and warmer\n    temperatures. Tangy citrus and pine hops aromas will be enhanced, as well as toasted\n    and dark malt aromas..\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Beers fermented with this strain will finish dry and crisp. This strain is at its best in\n    hop prominent American style ales. Very light ales may turn out a bit stripped, thin or\n    astringent if care is not taken with the mash temperature and avoiding over-extraction.\n    Acidity is moderately high, boosting hop flavors and creating a clipped finish.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    Remaining very neutral, this strain excels in strong ales with simple malt bills. Alcohol\n    will be a dominant flavor and aroma constituent, and may be quite warming but not\n    harsh."},
  {name: "Kolsch", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Giga Yeast", product_id: "GY021", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 79.0, max_attenuation: 83.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "Kolsch, Pale Ale, Alt, IPA, Cream Ale, Amber\n    Notes: From one of the oldest K&ouml;lsch breweries in K&ouml;ln.  Fermenting under 65&#730;F produces a very clean, crisp beer with a touch of ester.  Perfect for K&ouml;lsch or any style where a dry, clean profile is desired.  GY021 produces a moderate amount of sulfide that will dissipate completely."},
  {name: "Californian Lager", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M54", yeast_type: "Lager", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 82.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 68.0, description: "Suitable for California Common and lagers\n    fermented at ambient (ale) temperatures.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    California lager yeast produces a clean lager aroma without the associated sulphur this,\n    yeast is perfect for most kinds of lager.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    California lager yeast produces clean and crisp lagers, this yeast is excellent for\n    producing anything from a hoppy pilsner to a helles allowing excellent malt and hop\n    character to be expressed.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    With a medium alcohol tolerance this yeast is not designed for fermenting over 8.5%."},
  {name: "Empire Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M15", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 70.0, max_attenuation: 75.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 64.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "Suitable for Scottish Heavy Ales, American\n    Amber Ales, Sweet Stouts and more.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    When fermented at the correct temperature, Empire Ale yeast exhibits extremely\n    characterful and appetizing estery aromas reminiscent of rich dark fruit.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    This yeast strain has been carefully selected to aid mouth feel in the finished beer.\n    Body should be full leaning towards a rich dark fruit character. Care must be taken when\n    designing the beer to adjust hop bitterness to alleviate an over sweet finished beer.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    Higher alcohol beers will tend to be slightly too sweet and heavy due to the moderate\n    attenuative capabilities of the strain although a lower mash temperature may help the\n    fermentability and lower the final gravity."},
  {name: "Liberty Bell Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M36", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 74.0, max_attenuation: 78.0, flocculation: 2, min_temperature: 62.0, max_temperature: 74.0, description: "Suitable for both English and American Pale Ales,\n    Extra Special Bitters, Golden Ales and more\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Some pear esters, possibly strawberry or kiwi-like aromas can be expected. Clean,\n    delicate malt and hop aromas will survive fermentation. If hop and/or malt aromas are\n    prominent in the beer this strain&rsquo;s aroma characteristics will fade to the background.\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Clean, mostly neutral and smooth, finishes beers moderately dry but does not strip\n    away body. Silky, lightly smooth texture, light to medium body, mild acidity and mostly\n    neutral flavor. Aroma contributions from this yeast strain makes it a good all-rounder\n    for a wide range of ales.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    As a very good strain for strong ales, this yeast provides brews with plenty of body,\n    without being heavy or dense."},
  {name: "New World Strong Ale", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Mangrove Jack's", product_id: "M42", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Dry", cell_count: 50.0, min_attenuation: 77.0, max_attenuation: 82.0, flocculation: 3, min_temperature: 61.0, max_temperature: 72.0, description: "Suitable for IPAs, Porters, Russian\n    Imperial Stouts and more.\n    Notes: AROMA CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Hops and malt aromas are enhanced and will tend toward earthy, nutty, orange peel, and\n    mild spice. Esters will be nearly absent in normal strength beers fermented cool; below\n    68&deg;F (20&deg;C).\n    FLAVOR/MOUTHFEEL CHARACTERISTICS:\n    Beers fermented with this strain will finish dry, and very light beers will not be thin or\n    watery. Acidity will be low, and mouth feel will be light and soft on the palate with a\n    smooth non astringent texture. As this strain is highly flocculent and resilient and not\n    prone to autolysis, it is excellent for cask or bottle conditioning.\n    HIGHER ALCOHOL BEERS:\n    Ester formation will be slightly elevated in higher alcohol beers. The character of the\n    esters will be pleasant with ripe apple and pear dominating, along with faint banana.\n    Beer will be dry, but a perception of malt sweetness will survive in the aftertaste along\n    with malt character and complexity. Alcohol should be warming, not hot."},
  {name: "Denny's Favorite", user_id: 1, global: true, lab: "Wyeast Labs", product_id: "1450", yeast_type: "Ale", form: "Liquid", cell_count: 100.0, min_attenuation: 74.0, max_attenuation: 76.0, flocculation: 0, min_temperature: 60.0, max_temperature: 70.0, description: "American Ambers, Browns, IPAs, Scotch Ale, Brown Porter, Cream Ale, Fruit Beer, Red Ale\n    Notes: This terrific all-round yeast can be used for almost any beer style, and is a mainstay of one of our local homebrewers, Mr. Denny Conn. It is unique in that it produces a big mouthfeel and accentuates the malt, caramel, or fruit character of a beer without being sweet or under-attenuated. "},
